Latest Articles






TimesVideo

                    Driven | 2015 Cadillac Escalade ESV                
Because A-listers don’t roll in a Suburban.
Tom Voelk/Driven

















                    2 Basketball-Hoop Makers Order Repairs                
The Consumer Product Safety Commission said today that it would issue a warning to neighborhood basketball players about a protruding bolt on portable basketball hoops often used in driveways and cul-de-sacs. On Thursday, the commission will announce a recall of nearly two million portable basketball hoops after 28 reports that a bolt on the pole caused a variety of injuries, including lacerations that required 30 to 40 stitches.











                    COMPANY BRIEFS                
ESCALADE INC., Evansville, Ind., a maker of sporting goods, said it would buy the Step, an aerobic exercise system, from Bollinger Industries, Prairie View, Tex., a supplier of consumer fitness products. Terms were not disclosed. BLACK BOX CORP., Pittsburgh, a provider of computer-networking products and services to businesses, said it had bought closely held Telefuture Communications Ltd., New Rochelle, N.Y., a provider of cable design, installation and maintenance services. Terms were not disclosed.










COMPANY NEWS

                    ESCALADE CANCELS DEAL TO SELL SPORTING-GOODS BUSINESS                
Escalade Inc. said yesterday that it had canceled its agreement to sell its sporting-goods business to Sportcraft Ltd. In June, Escalade agreed to sell its Escalade Sports assets to the closely held Sportcraft for $74.5 million. The companies, which mutually agreed to terminate the deal, cited financing market uncertainties as a factor. Sportcraft, based in Mount Olive, N.J., the sports products company, had expressed doubts in August about its ability to finance the deal. Escalade, based in Evansville, Ind., makes sporting goods, office and graphic arts products. Shares of Escalade closed yesterday at $19, down 6.7 percent, or $1.375.










COMPANY NEWS

                    ESCALADE TO SELL ITS SPORTING GOODS BUSINESS                
Escalade Inc. agreed yesterday to sell its sporting goods equipment business to JEN Sports, a unit of the closely held Sportcraft Ltd, for $74.5 million to focus on its office and graphic arts business. Escalade, which had 1997 revenue of $91.5 million, makes basketball backboards and goals, pool tables and table tennis tables. The company employs 650 people, 400 of them in its sporting goods operations. Sportcraft, based in Mount Olive, N.J., makes darts, dart boards, table games and other sporting goods. The sale will allow Escalade to concentrate on expansion moves.


























